@wellthatwasodd Gross
You can not teach new behaviors by punishing people.

Anyway changing behavior is hard even for us to do for ourselves when we want to. But changing behavior in the absence of reinforcing outcomes usually doesn't turn out well, and that is why our criminal justice system doesn't work.

So if you want someone's behavior to change, find out what reinforces them and make that thing contingent on specific behavior. But guess what?  If you take something away to make it a reward, the brain sees that as punishment. Manipulating these parts of the brain has drawbacks.

How do brains decide what to see as positive?  Well it starts with some basic, primary instincts - food, comfort, social connection.  And then it grows as the brain associates other things with those primary instincts.  Your mom, approval, money.
What is reinforcement?  Whatever that person's brain percieves as a positive.  Not what you think they should view as positive, what they actually see as positive.
But if your goal is to teach pro social behaviors, to increase pro social behaviors, to teach adaptive skills, you NEED TO GIVE PEOPLE THE OPPORTUNITY FOR REINFORCEMENT

Now this is a key thing you need to understand about punishment.  Punishment is reinforcing to the punisher.  Smacking down someone you're annoyed with feels good, it feels like it works.  Seeing someone bad go to prison feels like justice.  How much of this is cultural?  Unknown

Think about learned helplessness and constant punishment in terms of society.  Our society gets this exactly backward.  Society believes the more and longer you punish someone, the better their behavior will be.  This is not how brains work!

In other words, to learn new skills and new adaptive behaviors, the brain needs reinforcement!  It needs to have a model that has good outcomes.  Here's the wiki page on learned helplessness. https://t.co/4dFUa6Crom

If the brain can't link punishment to something specific it can avoid, it can result in learned helplessness.  The brain ends up believing any behavior will result in a bad outcome.  Think about this in the context of the US prison system.

The brain isn't super smart in how it models behavior, so being punished frequently can result in decrease of desired behaviors like telling the truth.  And the punishment related anxiety can attach to people instead of behaviors.

Punishment decreases frequency of a behavior, while reinforcement increases frequency of a behavior (with all kinds of footnotes).  You can't use punishment to teach a new behavior or increase the frequency of a behavior.

However!  The brain has limitations!  Because actually brains are weird and complicated.

First, the brain has to be able to link the outcome to the behavior.
You're not always aware of these models but you use them anyway, even if they are trained on bad data (see: why therapy exists)

The brain builds models that predict outcomes of different choices, so you're more likely to do things the brain predicts will have a good outcome and less likely to do things the brain predicts will have a bad outcome.

Reinforcement = when something happens after a behavior that the brain percieves as positive.
Punishment = when something happens after a behavior that the brain percieves as negative/harmful.

Day before yesterday: 一昨日 ototoi (don't ask)
Two days: ２日 futsuka (the counter for days is ka)

Fun with Japanese reading.
Every day: 毎日 (mainichi, day is pronounced nichi)
One day: ある日 aruhi (day is pronounced hi)
Previous day: 前日 zenjitsu (day is pronounced jitsu)
Yesterday: 明日 ashita (doesn't have a sound for day in it even though it's written like it should)
